article.description:
Erin Buescher and Nicole Powell each scored
12 points to lead the Sacramento Monarchs to their seventh straight
win, 86-59 over the Minnesota Lynx on Saturday night.
article.headline: Monarchs earn day off after crushing struggling Lynx
article.linkText: Monarchs earn day off after crushing struggling Lynx
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- A loud cheer broke out in the Sacramento
Monarchs' locker room Saturday night when coach John Whisenant
rewarded his players with their first day off since training camp.

The team earned the Sunday rest with one of its best
performances of the season. They beat the Minnesota Lynx 86-59
Saturday night, tying their biggest margin of victory this season.

Erin Buescher and Nicole Powell each scored 12 points to lead
the Monarchs to their seventh straight win and ninth in 10 games.
They are three games behind Los Angeles in the Western Conference.

Kristin Haynie scored 11 points, Yolanda Griffith and Scholanda
Dorrell had nine, and Hamchetou Maiga-Ba and DeMya Walker both
added eight for the Monarchs (16-8), who have defeated Minnesota
seven straight times.

"It's fun being on a good team when anyone can attack and score
on any given night. It doesn't put the pressure on anyone in
particular," Buescher said. "It's nice knowing everyone is a
weapon and everyone is dangerous."

Seimone Augustus scored 20 to lead the last-place Lynx (8-15),
who scored fewer than 60 points for the second straight game.
Adrian Williams had 12, but no one else reached double figures.

"We have a real high pressure defense that is probably annoying
to play against," Buescher said.

The Lynx committed 24 turnovers, one off their season high.
Minnesota is the seventh straight team Sacramento has held to less
than 64 points.

"They do a great job of cutting off entry passes and making it
difficult for the point guard to make passes to the wings and then
they do a great job of fronting the post," said Tynesha Lewis, who
scored four points for Minnesota. "They're a very good team and we
didn't play well. So, that's a bad combination."

Six players scored during a 14-4 Sacramento run that gave the
Monarchs a 24-14 lead midway through the second quarter. The Lynx
came in with an average of 14.6 turnovers per game, the third
fewest in the league, but they committed 14 in the first half.

During one second-quarter stretch, Minnesota failed to get a
shot on three straight offensive trips. They threw a fast-break pass
out of bounds before committing an offensive foul and a 3-second
violation.

"Our defense is coming around to what made us a good team last
year," Whisenant said.

Baskets by Powell, Maiga-Ba and Ticha Penicheiro put the
Monarchs in front 44-25 just 2 minutes into the second half.

A jumper by Tamika Williams got Minnesota within 63-51 early in
the fourth quarter, but a 3-point play by Haynie started a 15-2
Sacramento run. That spurt was culminated with 3-pointers from
Powell and Penicheiro that made it 78-53 with under four minutes
left.
